Summary – LVM RAID1 Storage Configuration and I/O Performance Tuning
A new storage configuration has been implemented on the server **Dell PowerEdge R760 to improve both data resilience and I/O performance.
Two Dell Enterprise NVMe PM1735a 1.6TB disks were used to create a mirrored LVM RAID1 logical volume. This configuration provides data redundancy and ensures service continuity in case of a single disk failure.
The following operations were performed:
Initialization of the NVMe disks (nvme1n1 and nvme2n1)
Creation of the Volume Group (VG)
Creation of the Logical Volume (LV) using LVM RAID1 mirroring
Creation of the XFS filesystem
Mount configuration and persistence added in /etc/fstab
To ensure optimal NVMe performance, several operating system tuning adjustments were also verified and applied:
Confirmation of the none I/O scheduler, recommended for NVMe devices
Adjustment of the read-ahead value to 4096 KB to improve sequential read performance
Verification of the queue depth (nr_requests = 1023), suitable for high-performance NVMe devices
Confirmation that the devices are detected as non-rotational (rotational = 0)
Verification of maximum I/O size parameters (max_sectors_kb and max_hw_sectors_kb = 1024 KB)
These settings allow the system to fully leverage the Linux NVMe multi-queue architecture, improving I/O efficiency and reducing latency for applications relying on this storage.
The LVM mirror synchronization has been verified and completed successfully.
The storage configuration is now fully operational, redundant, and optimized for NVMe performance.
